      "side": 0,
      "message": "I checked what PropetyMap can read... turns out it can panic[1] on invalid bytes of memcache iff number it reads is a negative, while it expects a positive number of rows [2].\nIn fact, if you feed it the first 4 \"magic\" bytes of zstd (ie  28 b5 2f fd), it\u0027ll choke on the very first byte [3].\nSo, it\u0027s not perfect, but at least it won\u0027t silently read bad data.\n\n[1] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/infra/infra/+/master:go/src/go.chromium.org/luci/gae/service/datastore/deserialize.go;l\u003d216?q\u003ddatastore%2Fdeserialize.go%20panicIf\n[2] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/infra/infra/+/master:go/src/go.chromium.org/luci/common/data/cmpbin/number.go;l\u003d116?q\u003dcmpBin%20ReadUint\n[3] https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/infra/luci/luci-go/+/2560208 \n\nDo you remember that we have to re-deploy all GAE apps anyway due to change in auth library to use newer APIs?\nPerhaps we can take advantage of that to first deploy non-buggy code that would treat unknown compTypeByte as cacheMiss. Meanwhile, we can temporary signal via CacheImpl whether zstd can be used. Redis impl will do so from day 1, and ~Feb 2021, we can probably remove the hack and always encode with zstd.",
